The HyperMorphic Atomic-Holonomy Problem

Let

[
X_n={1,\ldots ,n},
\qquad
S_n={\text{all permutations of }X_n}.
]

Interpret each permutation (\sigma\in S_n) as a reversible computational law. Its inverse (\sigma^{-1}) gives exact state recovery.

For two laws (\sigma,\tau\in S_n), define their switching holonomy

[
\Omega(\sigma,\tau)

\sigma\tau\sigma^{-1}\tau^{-1}.
]

The pair is:

* flat when (\Omega(\sigma,\tau)=\mathrm{id});
* curved when (\Omega(\sigma,\tau)\neq\mathrm{id});
* atomically curved when (\Omega(\sigma,\tau)) is a (3)-cycle.

A (3)-cycle is the smallest possible nontrivial switching curvature: every commutator in (S_n) is an even permutation, and no nonidentity even permutation can move fewer than three states.

Define

[
\boxed{
H(n)=
\max\left{
|\mathcal L|:
\mathcal L\subseteq S_n,\
\Omega(\sigma,\tau)
\text{ is a (3)-cycle for every distinct }
\sigma,\tau\in\mathcal L
\right}.
}
]

The problem

Determine (H(n)).

More specifically:

1. Determine the asymptotic growth of (H(n)).
2. Decide whether there exists a universal constant (C) such that

[
H(n)\le Cn.
]

3. Classify the extremal families attaining (H(n)).
4. Determine whether every sufficiently large extremal family is generated by a small collection of geometric support patterns.
5. Determine the invariant-constrained version when every law must preserve a prescribed partition of (X_n).

Basic construction

For every (n\ge 3), consider the star family

[
\mathcal S_n

{(1,i):2\le i\le n}.
]

For distinct (i,j),

[
[(1,i),(1,j)]
]

is a (3)-cycle. Therefore

[
\boxed{H(n)\ge n-1.}
]

Initial exact values

Exact maximum-clique enumeration gives

[
H(3)=4,\qquad
H(4)=4,\qquad
H(5)=7,\qquad
H(6)=9.
]

These values suggest the following first major conjecture.

Atomic-Holonomy Conjecture

[
\boxed{H(n)=\Theta(n).}
]

A sharper target is

[
\boxed{H(n)\le 2n+O(1).}
]

Alternatively, constructing a superlinear family would disprove the conjecture and reveal a new high-density regime of reversible noncommuting laws.

Extremal pair-count version

For (m\le n!), define

[
U_n(m)

\max_{\substack{\mathcal L\subseteq S_n\|\mathcal L|=m}}
\left|
\left{
{\sigma,\tau}\subseteq\mathcal L:
[\sigma,\tau]\text{ is a (3)-cycle}
\right}
\right|.
]

Thus (U_n(m)) is the maximum number of unit-curvature law pairs among (m) reversible laws on (n) states.

The threshold function satisfies

[
H(n)=
\max\left{
m:
U_n(m)=\binom{m}{2}
\right}.
]

The broader Erdős-style question is therefore:

Among (m) reversible laws acting on (n) states, how many pairs can exhibit the smallest possible nonzero switching curvature?

Why it belongs to HyperMorphic mathematics

In this formulation:

[
\text{law}
\longleftrightarrow
\sigma,
]

[
\text{recoverability}
\longleftrightarrow
\sigma^{-1},
]

[
\text{law switching}
\longleftrightarrow
\sigma\tau,
]

[
\text{curvature or holonomy}
\longleftrightarrow
[\sigma,\tau],
]

[
\text{atomic curvature}
\longleftrightarrow
\text{(3)-cycle}.
]

The problem remains meaningful even when every AI, cybersecurity, physics, and quantum interpretation is removed. It is a standalone extremal problem in finite group theory, algebraic combinatorics, and discrete geometry.
